article.description: Mwadi Mabika scored 14 of her 22 points in the first 14 minutes as the Los Angeles Sparks clinched a playoff berth with an 80-62 victory over the Indiana Fever on Sunday.
article.headline: Mabika scores 22, Sparks clinch playoffs
article.linkText: Mabika makes impact as Sparks blast Fever
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Mwadi Mabika scored 14 of her 22 points in
the first 14 minutes as the Los Angeles Sparks clinched a playoff
berth with an 80-62 victory over the Indiana Fever on Sunday.

	   "Mwadi Mabika is phenomenal,'' Indiana coach Nell Fortner said.
"She's playing at another level than she was last year. I'm so
impressed with her. Mwadi has raised her game and has made this
team better.''

	   Lisa Leslie had 20 points and a game-high nine rebounds, and
DeLisha Milton added 12 points before fouling out with just over 8
minutes left. Tamecka Dixon scored 10 points for the Sparks (20-4).

	   "The last two days in practice we've really concentrated on
making better decisions with the basketball,'' Los Angeles coach
Michael Cooper said. "We went about this game with a different
mindset.''

	   Reserve Coquese Washington scored 11 of her 14 points in the
first half for Indiana (10-14). Nadine Malcolm added 12 points and
Tamika Catchings 10.

	   Mabika scored six points during a 12-0 run as the Sparks
extended their lead to 22-6 with 12:07 remaining before the break.

	   "She shoots the ball so well,'' Fortner said. "From different
areas on the floor, she's so strong.''

	   The Fever, who trailed 41-26 at halftime, closed within 11 on a
3-pointer by Monica Maxwell with 13:55 left.

	   The Sparks went on a nine-point run, pushing their lead to 59-39
with 11:52 remaining. Los Angeles led by at least 14, and as many
as 21 points, the rest of the way.

	   The Sparks won their fourth straight and moved two games ahead
of Houston in the Western Conference.

	   "At the beginning of the season, we just wanted to come out and
play and play efficiently,'' Cooper said. "And we got ourselves
caught in some traps by turning the ball over, not rebounding,
leaning the other way rather than getting the ball first.''

	   Indiana has lost all four of its games in Los Angeles since
joining the league in 2000.

	   The attendance at Staples Center was announced at 13,141.
